		<item>
		<title>Being Creative</title>
		<link>https://llgt.cafe/being-creative</link>
					<comments>https://llgt.cafe/being-creative#respond</comments>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[llgt]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Thu, 20 Apr 2023 17:58:06 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Creativity]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[LLGT]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://llgt.cafe/?p=734</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Creativity is something that we are born with. And as soon as we are able, with few exceptions, we all start creating things. it may be finger paints or the drawing on the hallway wall. It’s very unlikely that, at the age of six, we&#160;<a class="read-more" href="https://llgt.cafe/being-creative">&#8230;</a>]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p>Creativity is something that we are born with. And as soon as we are able, with few exceptions, we all start creating things. it may be finger paints or the drawing on the hallway wall. It’s very unlikely that, at the age of six, we are creating masterpieces but, given the resources, being creative is something that comes natural.</p>



<p>The problem is that, with age, many of us loose the desire to be creative. In jr. high, I really enjoyed drawing. And when I had a decent teacher, I did fairly well. But there were things that made me decide not to pursue art in high school. At the same time, I picked up on photography and never let it go.</p>



<p>As far as drawing, it is something that I would really have to work at. And, right now, I don’t really have the desire.</p>



<p>Creativity may be something that comes, but skill is something that we have to work on. Some people pick up on a form of art more easily but whatever we choose to do, we have to work on it, practicing to get better and better.</p>



<p>Focusing on the tools of the craft — cameras for photographers, brushes for painters and microphones for singers — may be exciting, but the most important tool is the mind. It’s the ability to think of new ways of doing things and the desire to learn new techniques that helps us to stand out.</p>



<p>For many, the art that we create matter only to us. Some are able to become professionals in their craft. Few have had their work stand the test of time. Yet, it’s important that we are able to find a way to express ourselves in one way or another.</p>



<p>If you find yourself unable to get out, now may be a perfect time to sharpen your skills. Even with restrictions, I’m still able to get out and take pictures. And, if I really worked at it, I could find things to photograph indoors.</p>



<p>Right now, I’m working more on my writing. I’m not sure whether I’m getting better or not, but it’s something that I enjoy doing. If someone else enjoys reading what I have to write, that’s just an added bonus.</p>



<p>What is it that you enjoy doing? Is there something that you used to do that you would like to get back to doing? Maybe there is something that you can teach to others. Or maybe you can just hone your skills.</p>



<p>Your work may just matter to you, but it still matters. You may not have the skills of a master, but don’t compare yourself with others. Your job is to get better than you wire yesterday, or a hundred yesterdays ago. And, whatever your skill level, don’t give up.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
					<wfw:commentRss>https://llgt.cafe/being-creative/feed</wfw:commentRss>
			<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
		
		
			</item>
		<item>
		<title>Growing Imagination</title>
		<link>https://llgt.cafe/growing-imagination</link>
					<comments>https://llgt.cafe/growing-imagination#respond</comments>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[llgt]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sun, 09 Apr 2023 14:46:11 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Creativity]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Personal Growth]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[LLGT]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://llgt.cafe/?p=698</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[“Imagination is more important than knowledge. Knowledge is limited. Imagination encircles the world.” ―Albert Einstein Imagination is built on what we know. But it may also be limited by what we know. It’s taking what we know, and asking the what if questions. What if&#160;<a class="read-more" href="https://llgt.cafe/growing-imagination">&#8230;</a>]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p>“Imagination is more important than knowledge. Knowledge is limited. Imagination encircles the world.” ―Albert Einstein</p>



<p>Imagination is built on what we know. But it may also be limited by what we know. It’s taking what we know, and asking the what if questions. What if we put these two things together. What if we made this smaller. What if we used this instead of that.</p>



<p>“Imagination is the source of every form of human achievement. And it&#8217;s the one thing that I believe we are systematically jeopardizing in the way we educate our children and ourselves.”<br>― Sir Ken Robinson</p>



<p>The more we know, the more we have to work with. Yet, imagination is not necessarily limited by our knowledge. It is limited only by our desire to try new things. It is not necessarily limited by our resources, but by our ability to believe in what we can and cannot do.</p>



<p>Children have some of the most active imaginations. As children, there seems to be no limit to what we can do, who we can be, or what we can create. But there are certain things that we need in order to exercise our imaginations.</p>



<p>For one, we need to put the right things into our minds, or our imaginations will take us down the wrong path. Reading, exploring, and listening are just a few things that we can do to help build our imaginations.</p>



<p>Having a safe place is another thing that we need in order to activate our imaginations. We can’t be worried about our own safety and use our imaginations at the same time. If we worry about what tomorrow might bring, we may be using our imagination, but probably in the wrong way. We need a place that we can get away from the worry and the business of the world around us so that we can imagine what could be.</p>



<p>A safe place may be out in the woods, your favorite chair at your favorite cafe, your own bed. For those who choose meditation, they find their safe place in their mind. A safe place is some place that we are free to think, free to ask questions and, most importantly, it’s a place that we are free from judgment.</p>



<p>We also need time: time to think, to dream, to ask questions and to wonder “what if.” If we’re too busy, have too many things on our mind, or just too tired to think, we won’t be able to creatively use our imaginations.</p>



<p>If our imagination is to be successful, we will also need the freedom to try, to experiment, to create hypotheses and to test them. We need the freedom to try new things. And we need the freedom to fail, or just to find out what doesn’t work, depending on how you look at it.</p>



<p>If we are to accomplish greater things, we will need to combine our resources and use the imaginations of others. Others can bring their own understanding as well as knowledge that we may lack. And together, we can find answers that we might never find on our own.</p>



<p>Imagination may just be the start, but it’s where everything starts. Every actin, every invention, and every work of art began as a though or a question. How are you using your imagination? What are you dreaming of?</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
					<wfw:commentRss>https://llgt.cafe/growing-imagination/feed</wfw:commentRss>
			<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
		
		
